, Satoshi Nakamoto states that Internet commerce has become very reliant
 on having third-party institutions process electronic payments.
 According to him, this model of commerce prevents completely non-reversible
 transactions, which results to several disadvantages.
 What is needed is an electronic payment system that relies on cryptographic
 proof, which will enable non-reversible transactions and remove the said
 disadvantages.
 However, a prominent problem in electronic payment systems is 
\emph on
double-spending
\emph default
, or the possibility that a person may cheat by sending the same unit of
 digital currency to two different people.
 As such, Nakamoto presents a decentralized solution to the double-spending
 problem through a peer-to-peer network which timestamps transactions.
 In this peer-to-peer network, all transactions are announced to all participati
ng nodes.
 When a node receives a transaction, it checks for its validity and then
 places them in a block along with other transactions to be timestamped.
 The node then performs proof of work by computing a hash of the items in
 the block until it meets certain specifications.
 When such a hash has been successfully computed, the node will then broadcast
 the block to the other nodes in the network.
 The other nodes in the network will then check the validity of the transactiion
s in the block and express their acceptance by creating the next block and
 including the hash of the previous block in the computation of the next
 hash.
 These actions result to each node having a chain of blocks 
