\begin_layout Section
Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Satoshi Nakamoto's paper presents some very novel ideas.
 His
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Satoshi Nakamoto is just an alias for the author of the paper.
 As such, we don't really know the true identity of the author of the paper.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 paper shows an alternative to the current digital commerce system which
 is more private and more affordable for the buyers and sellers.
 Furthermore, the paper also shows a novel application for proof-of-work
 algorithms.
 The benefits promised by the ideas in the paper have been shown to be very
 real by present-day cryptocurrencies.
 However, despite the novelty of the paper, the paper is not without issues.
 First, the paper lacks a review of related literature.
 As such, the reader of the paper is deprived of the opportunity to know
 where the paper stands in terms of the larger body of knowledge surrounding
 it.
 Furthermore, a reader which is not familiar with the field of digital currencie
s might become confused when reading the paper as it doesn't give necessary
 background information regarding terms such as double-spending.
 Such lack of background information can be attributed to the lack of a
 review of related literature in the paper.
 Second, the idea of the peer-to-peer network proposed by Nakamoto is dependent
 on the assumption that a large number of devices will be participating
 in the network.
 Since the network depends on having honest nodes control a majority of
 the network, if there are only a few devices running the network and a
 malicious third party decides to introduce a large number of nodes which
 is controlled by them, then that third party will have the power to choose
 which transactions get accepted into a block or not, thus negating the
 decentralized aspect of the network.
